      "content": "Absolutely, it's always wise to consider all possibilities. In addition to nitrogen deficiency, other factors could be at play. Overwatering is a common issue that can lead to root rot, which in turn can cause yellowing leaves. Ensure your plants have well-draining soil and that you're not overwatering them. Pests like aphids, spider mites, or even root-feeding nematodes could also be the culprits, so keep an eye out for any signs of infestation. Lastly, diseases such as early blight or fusarium wilt can cause yellowing leaves, so inspect your plants for any unusual spots or patterns on the leaves. If you find any pests or disease, you may need to treat your plants with appropriate organic or chemical solutions. Keep your garden healthy, and your plants will thrive, free from goblin-like troubles!",
